<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{@FG{{@KJ{{cut}}:ki}}ru}}}} functions as a auxiliary verb attached to the @HI{{masu}}-stem of a verb and gives the meaning of "to do something completely".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{koredakeno@FG{{@KJ{{Sino-^character}}:kanji}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{memorize}}:obo}}e@EM{{kiremasu}}ka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Can you memorise this many kanji?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When attached to a non-volitional verb, @HI{{@EM{{@FG{{@KJ{{cut}}:ki}}ru}}}} indicates that someone gets completely into the state expressed by the preceding verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{tired}}:tsuka}}re@EM{{kitte}}te,@FG{{@KJ{{phantasm}}:maboroshi}}wo@KJ{{see}}tadakejanaika.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Oh, she just had a hallucination from the exhaustion.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{@FG{{@KJ{{cut}}:ki}}ru}}}} attached to the @HI{{masu}}-stem of a verb of motion means from the beginning to the end.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{he}}ha@KT{{marason}}de42.195}}km@HI{{wo@KJ{{run}}ri@EM{{kitta}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    He completed 42.195km in the marathon.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In the negative potential form, @HI{{@EM{{@FG{{@KJ{{cut}}:ki}}renai}}}}, the auxiliary gives the meaning of "to be unable to finish".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{go@FG{{@KJ{{meal}}:han}}no@FG{{@KJ{{quantity}}:ryou}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{many}}:oo}}kute,@KJ{{eat}}be@EM{{@KJ{{cut}}renai}}yo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I cannot finish the rice because there is so much.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The suffix @HI{{@EM{{kiru}}}} is similar to the suffix <a href="grammar-owaru-suffix.html">@HI{{owaru}}</a>.
The difference is that the former carries a nuance that something has been carried out until the end and nothing is left.
So @KJ{{drink}}@HI{{mikiru}} suggests that a drink has been completely finished and that none of drink is left over.
</p>

